def: To look over; to supervise. [Obs.] B. Jonson.
The quality or condition of being base; degradation; vileness.I once did hold it a baseness to write fair. Shak.
The horney covering of the lower mandible of a bird.
To give inconvenience or trouble to; to disturb or molest; todiscommode; to worry; to put out; as, we are incommoded by want ofroom.

Disposed to solicit; eager to obtain something desirable, or toavoid anything evil; concerned; anxious; careful. "Solicitous of myreputation." Dryden. "He was solicitous for his advice." Calerendon.Enjoy the present, whatsoever it be, and be not solicitous about thefuture. Jer. Taylor.The colonel had been intent upon other things, and not enoughsolicitous to finish the fortifications. Clarendon.-- So*lic"it*ous*ly, adv.-- So*lic"it*ous*ness, n.
The act of resorbing; also, the act of absorbing again;reabsorption.
To indue or imbue (a body) with soul. [R.] Emerson.
